SACRAMENTO (AP) - A Senate committee investigating possible price gouging in=
=20
California's energy market voted unanimously Wednesday to ask the full Senat=
e=20
to find Houston-based Reliant Energy in contempt for failing to comply with =
a=20
subpoena for documents.=20
The decision came despite Reliant's last-ditch offer to turn over 10,000=20
documents under a contingent confidentiality agreement that the Senate Selec=
t=20
Committee to Investigate Market Manipulation rejected.
"I'm not just trying to buy time," said Reliant attorney Charles J. Stevens.=
=20
"We believe we have acted cooperatively. We believe we have a good-faith=20
legal dispute."=20
"It's clear you're trying to work with us. It's not contempt with contempt,"=
=20
agreed committee Chair Joseph Dunn, D-Santa Ana.=20
By contrast, Sen. Steve Peace, D-Chula Vista, blasted Reliant's "shoddy=20
behavior" before backing what he termed "a legally unprecedented step."=20
If the full Senate imposes sanctions against Reliant, it will be the first=20
time since 1929, when the Senate voted to jail reluctant witnesses during a=20
committee investigation of price fixing and price gouging allegations=20
involving cement sales to the state.=20
There are no set penalties, said committee special counsel Laurence Drivon.=20
By law, "the Senate can take such action as it deems necessary and=20
appropriate."=20
The contempt citation will be presented to the Senate Thursday, but will=20
immediately be sent to the Rules Committee for another hearing before the=20
full Senate acts, Dunn said.=20
He said the committee had no choice but to seek the sanctions and likely=20
force a court battle after it was unable to reach agreement with Reliant ove=
r=20
the confidentiality of its documents. The committee voted 6-0 in favor of th=
e=20
contempt finding.=20
"If we reach agreement on these issues, the process would be terminated=20
immediately," Dunn said.=20
In that light, the committee stepped back from its contempt vote last week=20
against Enron Corp. after the company and committee moved closer to agreemen=
t=20
over its release of thousands of documents stored in Texas.=20
Enron sued the committee last week to stop the subpoena of its financial and=
=20
electricity trading records. Among its objections are that only the Federal=20
Energy Regulatory Commission has the authority to investigate wholesale=20
markets.=20
Reliant, like Enron, had argued the company's financial papers are outside=20
the committee's jurisdiction because most of its operations and paperwork ar=
e=20
outside California.=20
Atlanta-based Mirant Inc. also at least temporarily avoided a contempt=20
citation by agreeing to turn over subpoenaed documents. The committee will=20
review both companies' compliance in 30 days.

