Calif. Senate Panel Votes To Cite Reliant With Contempt

07/18/2001
Dow Jones Energy Service
(Copyright (c) 2001, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.)

LOS ANGELES -(Dow Jones)- A California Senate committee Wednesday voted to=20
cite Reliant Energy (REI) with contempt because the company has refused to=20
provide documents for an investigation into wholesale electricity prices in=20
the state, said committee Chairman Joe Dunn, D-Santa Ana.=20
The committee also voted to forward a contempt charge for Enron Corp (ENE) t=
o=20
the full Senate, where it will be voted on. If the charge is approved, the=20
Senate will vote on punishment, which could include hefty fines or=20
incarceration of executives.
Talks between Enron and committee attorneys Monday seemed to indicate the=20
company would agree to committee demands, but since then it has become clear=
=20
the company doesn't plan to comply, Dunn said.=20
"If you had asked two days ago I'd have said we are cautiously optimistic=20
about Enron. Now I'm pessimistic about it. We felt they were indicating to u=
s=20
a willingness to do what the other generators were willing to do, but the=20
bottom line is that they are not, despite their cooperative-sounding words.=20
We are no closer to them coming into compliance than we were a week ago,"=20
Dunn said.=20

The Senate Select Committee to Investigate Market Manipulation is requesting=
=20
that Reliant and Enron provide 16 kinds of documents related to market=20
behavior, rent a depository for the documents, and sign the committee's=20
version of a confidentiality agreement. Both generators have refused to meet=
=20
those demands, Dunn said.=20
The committee will drop its contempt charges at any time before a full Senat=
e=20
vote if either generator agrees to its requests.=20
A report detailing Enron's contempt charge will be sent to the full Senate o=
n=20
Thursday for introduction, but is expected to be referred to the Senate Rule=
s=20
Committee for review before a floor vote.=20
Dunn said he didn't know how long the report would be considered in the Rule=
s=20
Committee, but he will "certainly push them to do it as soon as possible."=20
Enron spokesman Mark Palmer said the company "will continue to negotiate"=20
with the committee.=20
Legislators are scheduled to begin a monthlong break Friday, but aren't=20
certain that will happen because they still need to pass a budget bill and=20
are trying to approve a bill to rescue Edison International (EIX) unit=20
Southern California Edison before leaving.=20
Dunn said it would take a few days to prepare a report on Reliant's contempt=
=20
charge.=20
"We may not be able to forward that report to the Senate floor until the day=
=20
we get back from recess," Dunn said.=20
No one at Reliant could be immediately reached for comment.=20
The committee originally was poised to cite seven other electricity=20
generators for contempt, but all eventually agreed to provide the requested=20
information.=20
